Below I’ve written a single, complete release-management workflow for CureMD — how release packages are created and sent, the timelines for each activity (monthly / weekly / daily), who does what, and the exact live-issue (production) resolution path. I’ve pulled the process directly from your Release Management document for CureMD (May 14, 2025). 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


High-level overview
CureMD runs three release frequencies:

Monthly releases — for planned SCRUM deliverables (features/stories). This is the full, formal release cycle.

Weekly releases — for servers that can only be accessed weekly (client servers that are not available daily).

Daily releases — for live (L1) production issues that must be fixed and deployed the very next day.

All releases result in a release package (a working piece of software) that is deployed to one or more types of live servers: App servers (CureMD-owned), County servers (client-owned), and Client servers (client-owned, accessed over VPN). Deployments to client servers follow a shipment plan (calendar of which client/servers get shipped on which date).

Monthly release workflow (detailed — stages, who, and timelines)
Monthly releases follow a fixed set of stages. Below I list each stage with purpose, who owns it, and typical duration.

Release Tagging

Purpose: Identify all user stories intended for the upcoming package.

Ownership: Scrum teams (developers & QAs) tag stories after local testing; QA members do the QA tagging.

Key rule / timeline: Tagging cutoff is 2 weeks before rollout. Stories must be communicated to QA-Integration 2 sprints before rollout. Scrum teams must move stories to “Ready for Deployment”. If stories miss the cutoff, QA-Integration will NOT include them.

Notes: Any production alarms/bugs remain QA-Integration’s responsibility; scrum teams must handover timely.

Baseline Merging

Purpose: Prepare the QA-Integration baseline environment by merging dev branches into baseline.

Ownership: Developers (perform merges) + QA-Integration (stabilizes baseline).

Conflict resolution: Developers merge their local branches into the baseline and resolve any merge conflicts immediately (“there and then”) so baseline stabilizes.

Package Preparation for Baseline

Purpose: Build/package code for deployment to baseline server.

Ownership: QA-Integration / SCM/DevOps support.

Timeline: 1 business day.

Baseline Testing

Purpose: QA-Integration runs audits and tests on baseline server.

Ownership: QA-Integration.

Timeline: 4–5 business days.

Action: Bugs discovered are prioritized and fixed by devs.

Release Notes

Purpose: Document technical/setup details of features in the package.

Ownership: QA-Integration (with inputs from developers).

Timeline: 1 business day.

Package Preparation (for Release Server)

Purpose: Create the release package intended for the release server (next step before production).

Ownership: SCM/DevOps / QA-Integration.

Timeline: 1 business day.

Release / Regression Testing

Purpose: Deploy package to release server and perform regression/integration testing.

Ownership: QA-Integration.

Timeline: ~2 business days.

Live Server Rollouts

Purpose: Deploy package to live servers and roll out features to end-users.

Ownership: DevOps/SCM, QA-Integration, sometimes Interfaces team (for interface deployments).

Timing: Rollouts start the very next day after release/regression testing closes.

Servers: App servers, County servers, Client servers (over VPN). For client servers, deployments follow a dedicated shipment plan (date → target servers/practices).

Key monthly timings (summary):

Tagging cutoff = 2 weeks before rollout

Baseline package prep = 1 day

Baseline testing = 4–5 days

Release notes = 1 day

Release package prep = 1 day

Regression testing = 2 days

Rollout = starts next day after regression testing

How packages are made & moved (packaging + shipment)
Developers merge validated branches into the baseline. QA-Integration prepares a baseline package and deploys it to the baseline server for QA validation.

After baseline testing and fixes, QA-Integration prepares the release package for the release server. This package is the artifact that will move to production.

Release package → Release server for final regression. After sign-off, the package is deployed to live server(s) according to the shipment plan.

Shipment plan lists which App/County/Client servers get the release and on which date (this is used to schedule rollouts, especially for client and county servers).

For Interfaces (integration components), CICD pipelines may not exist; Interfaces team often manually move DLLs/files to target production servers and owns that deployment end-to-end.

Weekly release cycle (brief)
Used for client servers accessible on a weekly schedule (not every day).

Runs every Thursday.

QA-Integration prepares the weekly release package and performs integration/regression testing.

Scrum teams are usually not involved in weekly release preparation.

Daily release cycle (how live issues are fixed & deployed — step-by-step)
This is the most important flow for resolving live production issues (L1):

Consolidation

Client production issues reported on Day N are consolidated and shared with Engineering.

Analysis & Fix

Development teams analyze the L1 bugs and implement fixes on Day N.

QA Testing

QA tests the developer’s fix.

Create Deployment Task

Once QA approves, developer creates a Deployment Task that links the PR and obtains required approvals (on the PR and the Deployment Task).

Deployment Task MUST have a proper category (e.g., live issue, security fix, etc.).

Cutoffs & Deployment Times

Cutoff for merges/approvals: 12:45 PM PKT — any merges/approvals after this time are not included in that day’s release.

Deployment from release server to production is scheduled for packages that have Deployment Tasks approved at or before 12:45 PM.

Deployment start (cutoff): 1:00 PM (package must be ready by then to be deployed).

Post-deploy verification (release server)

After deployment, developer changes the Deployment Task status from Approved → Deployed.

1:00 PM – 2:00 PM: QA verifies the package on the release server (this is crucial — the release server holds the same package that goes to production).

QA must comment/confirm on the Deployment Task by 2:00 PM. If not, the fix will NOT be included in that package.

Handover to QA-Integration

QA-Integration then updates workflow from Deployed → SAT Done.

Production deployment

2:00 PM – 3:00 PM: DevOps/SCM deploys the package to production.

Scrum QA verification

After production deployment, scrum QA verifies the fix directly on the specific client environment where the issue originated.

Upon successful verification, QA posts confirmation in the “DC Quality Assurance” MS Teams group.

Flow of statuses for Deployment Task:
Created/Approved → (developer deploys) → Deployed → (QA verification) → SAT Done → (DevOps deploy to prod) → final verification and confirmation in Teams.

Interfaces release management (special case)
Interfaces often do not follow the standard cycle because their changes have broad/systemic impact.

The Interfaces team owns deployments (DevOps/QA-Integration are not involved).

Because CICD pipelines may not exist for interfaces, deployment is often manual (copying DLLs/files to target servers).

If Interfaces timelines align, they may tag their work to be included in standard monthly packages.

Shipment plan & client rollouts
Live rollouts are coordinated using a shipment plan (example: the image you provided shows deployments scheduled across several dates and App/County targets in November 2025).

Client servers (hosted outside CureMD network) require access via VPN and are deployed to according to that schedule.

App servers (CureMD-owned) usually follow the standard rollout date once release/regression testing is complete.

Responsibilities (quick matrix)
Scrum teams / Developers

Build code, unit test, merge to baseline, fix merge conflicts immediately, move stories to Ready for Deployment.

Create Deployment Tasks for L1 fixes and link PRs.

Scrum QA

Initial QA on team test servers.

Test fixes on release server (daily cycle) and verify in client environment after production deploy.

QA-Integration

Manage baseline and release environments, perform audits, baseline testing, release/regression testing, prepare release notes, and decide final package contents.

Responsible for production alarms/bugs and enforcing cutoffs (do not include stories that missed tagging cutoff).

DevOps / SCM

Assist packaging, deploy to production, and coordinate live rollouts.

Deploy between 2:00–3:00 PM during daily cycle.

Interfaces team

Own deployment of interface components (manual movement of artifacts when CICD is absent).

How live issues are resolved (practical checklist for L1)
If you’re resolving a live (production L1) issue, follow this checklist:

Triage & assign the issue immediately (Day N).

Dev: implement fix and raise PR (same day).

QA: test fix and give approval.

Create Deployment Task, link PR, add proper category (live issue, security, ...).

Get approvals BEFORE 12:45 PM PKT (missing this means next day).

1:00 PM: deploy to release server (developer updates task → Deployed).

1:00–2:00 PM: QA verifies on release server and comments on the Deployment Task (by 2:00 PM).

QA-Integration marks SAT Done once accepted.

2:00–3:00 PM: DevOps deploys to production.

Post-deploy: scrum QA verifies client environment and posts confirmation on DC Quality Assurance MS Teams group.

Rules, cutoffs, and common reasons a story gets excluded
Tagging cutoff for monthly release: 2 weeks before rollout.

Daily approvals cutoff for L1: 12:45 PM PKT (deploy at 1:00 PM).

QA comment cutoff for release verification: 2:00 PM — if QA doesn’t confirm by then, the fix is out of that day’s deployment window.

If a story misses cutoff or QA/Integration flags it, it will not be included in package — plan to include in next cycle.

Practical tips & best practices (to reduce friction)
Plan stories early and communicate to QA-Integration 2 sprints beforehand.

Resolve merge conflicts locally while merging to baseline — do not leave conflicts unresolved.

Categorize Deployment Tasks properly (live issue, security fix) so approvals and prioritization are clear.

Ensure PR approvals and Deployment Task approvals are complete well before cutoffs (12:45 PM).

Keep release notes up to date and include setup instructions for operations/clients.

For Interfaces, document manual steps clearly since deployment is manual and often fragile.

Where to look / reference
