20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


1) Technical Support — Live Issues & L3 Requests (Playbook)
Goal: quickly identify root cause, ensure the fix has correct test coverage, and push a safe patch via the daily/monthly release process.

Responsibilities
Technical Support / Assigned team member(s): Triage, debug, coordinate fix, perform root-cause analysis, create PR/Deployment Task.

Person actually resolving the case (developer): provides technical details, code changes, and rollback plan.

Tester / Scrum QA: defines and executes verification scenarios to ensure coverage of changed code.

QA-Integration & DevOps: final checks, package deployment, production rollout.

Rule: Always ask the person actually resolving the case the questions below — they must confirm root cause, code locations, and verification steps.

Investigation checklist (what Tech Support must collect)
Ticket summary & priority (L1 / L2 / L3) and a short reproduction summary.

Exact environment where issue occurred (App, County, Client, server name, IP, DB).

Time-window of occurrence + client/tenant affected.

Full reproduction steps (minimal steps to reproduce).

Expected vs actual behavior and any error messages / stacktrace / SQL error.

Relevant logs (application logs, web server, database logs) with timestamps.

Recent deploys/changes (PRs/commits that touched the area — include PR links).

Screenshots / recordings if UI issue.

DB changes / Data sample (if data-dependent) — obfuscate PHI if necessary.

Accessibility/permissions: confirm whether the bug is tenant-specific or global.

Technical questions to ask the developer (must be answered)
What is the root cause (code / config / data / infra)?

Which files & services were changed (PR link)?

Is the fix a code-only, DB-only, or code+DB change? (If DB: include migration scripts)

Does the fix require configuration or setup for any clients? (release notes entry)

Are there side effects or regression risk areas?

Is a hotfix required or can it go through the daily release?

What is the rollback/revert plan if deployment fails?

Are there any sensitive data or special security considerations?

Who is the owner for post-deploy verification and for communication with the customer?

Tester collaboration: establishing verification & coverage
When the tester (scrum QA) works with the developer, they must define and document explicit verification scenarios that cover:

Happy path: the exact reproduction steps & expected results.

Negative/edge cases: malformed inputs, large payloads, missing permissions.

Data integrity: verify DB rows, FK constraints, no duplicate or orphaned data.

Multi-tenant considerations: verify other tenants are not affected.

Cross-module impact: test related flows/modules that call the changed code.

Security & permissions: ensure no escalation or data leak.

Performance/smoke: basic performance check (DB queries within acceptable range).

Rollback verification: confirm rollback steps return system to pre-change state.

Tester must document test cases in the Deployment Task and confirm they’re executed (pass/fail) during release/regression and after production deployment.

Communication & collaboration protocol
Tech Support adds all items to the ticket (logs, PR link, owner, test cases).

Daily sync: for L1/L3 issues in the sprint, Technical Support + Developer + Tester join a quick standup (10–15 mins) to align on scope and timeline.

Status updates are posted in the ticket and a dedicated Teams channel (e.g., #dc-quality-assurance) when production verification succeeds.

For L3: Escalate to QA-Integration/Team Lead if impact is broad or requires shipping beyond daily cycle.

2) Processes — Release Management (focus: REL Cycle, Deployment Tasks, Daily packages)
This expands the CureMD REL Cycle into a deploy-focused runbook so every actor (Dev, Scrum QA, QA-Integration, DevOps) knows the gates and tasks.

REL Cycle — short recap (monthly / weekly / daily)
Monthly: feature releases. Stages: Release Tagging → Baseline Merging → Baseline Package → Baseline Testing (4–5 days) → Release Notes → Release Package → Release/Regression Testing (~2 days) → Live Rollouts (start next day). (Tagging cutoff = 2 weeks before rollout.)

Weekly: for client servers that are accessible weekly (Thursday pipeline). QA-Integration prepares weekly package. Scrum teams usually not involved.

Daily: for live issues (L1). Fix on Day N → test & Deployment Task → deploy Day N+1. (Cutoff times apply.)

Deployment Tasks — canonical template & required fields
Every Deployment Task (DT) must include:

Title: short description (e.g., L1 - Fix patient-portal session timeout - Client X)

Ticket/Issue ID (link to JIRA/TFS/YouTrack)

Category: live issue, security fix, bugfix, hotfix, etc. (mandatory)

Priority: L1/L2/L3

PR link(s): link to the code review / commits

Artifact/Package: name/version/sha of package to deploy

Target environment(s): Release Server, Production, ClientName-Server

Planned deploy window: date & time (for daily: aligns with 1:00–3:00 PM window)

Approvals: list of required approvers (PR approvals, QA sign-off, Release Manager)

Verification checklist: test cases (happy/negative/cross-module), expected pass criteria

Rollback plan: steps to revert or redeploy prior artifact + DB revert instructions if DB change involved

Owner(s): developer, scrum QA, deployment owner (DevOps)

Release notes / setup steps: brief instructions if any client-specific config required

Status: Created → Approved → Deployed → SAT Done → Released (or Rolled Back)

Mandatory: DT must have PR linked and all approvals on PR + DT before deployment window.

Daily package deployment — step-by-step (time windows & who does what)
This is the deterministic daily flow used for L1 fixes (Day N → Day N+1):

Cutoffs & windows

12:45 PM PKT — final cutoff for merges & approvals. Any merges or approvals after this will not be included in that day’s release.

1:00 PM — Deployment to release server begins (for approved deployment tasks).

1:00–2:00 PM — QA verifies on the release server and must comment on the DT by 2:00 PM.

2:00–3:00 PM — DevOps/SCM deploys to production (or specific client server).

Post 3:00 PM — Scrum QA must verify fix in client environment and post confirmation in DC Quality Assurance.

Detailed steps

Developer pushes fix, opens PR, gets code review. Developer updates the DT with PR link, description, and verification checklist once QA approves on the sprint test environment.

Approvals: the PR and DT must have required approvals by 12:45 PM. Developer flags the DT as Approved.

1:00 PM: Developer/DevOps deploys the approved package to the release server. Developer updates DT status to Deployed.

1:00–2:00 PM: QA executes the DT verification checklist on the release server. QA must comment & sign off on the DT by 2:00 PM (otherwise the fix is excluded).

QA-Integration updates DT to SAT Done when satisfied.

2:00–3:00 PM: DevOps/SCM deploys package to production.

Scrum QA verifies fix on the specific client environment (or App server) and, upon success, posts confirmation in the DC Quality Assurance Teams group. DT is marked Released.

If failure occurs at any check, follow rollback plan or stop the pipeline and escalate immediately.

Release → Regression (how Daily package moves)
The release server mirrors the production package and is the staging zone for final verification (regression tests). The daily package is verified here before promotion to production.

Regression testing on the release server is typically lighter for daily releases (focus on smoke & the DT test cases). For monthly, regression is more exhaustive (2 days).

Handover: when QA completes regression on release server (and documents results), the DT handover to DevOps indicates readiness for production.

Status transitions (recommended)
Use explicit DT statuses so everyone understands the current gate:

Created → In Review → Approved (PR approvals complete & DT approved) → Deployed (release server) → SAT Done (QA-Integration acceptance) → Released (production, verified by scrum QA) → Closed (post-deploy tasks done)
If something goes wrong: Rolled Back → Created for rework.

3) L3 Requests — special handling & escalation
Definition: L3 are more complex issues that often require deeper domain knowledge or cross-team changes (DB schema, infra, interfaces).

Investigation: same initial checklist as L1, but requires a detailed RCA and multiple environment reproductions.

Coordination: involve Integration / Interfaces or DB owners early. If interfaces are involved, one must consider the Interfaces team’s manual deployment process.

Scheduling: L3 may not be eligible for daily release if it needs extensive testing or changes; schedule for next monthly or weekly run or create an exception after Risk Assessment.

Approval: L3 changes must have a higher-level signoff (Team Lead / Release Manager) if they bypass standard cycles.

4) Example Deployment Task – minimal required content (copy/paste template)
Title: [L1] Fix: <short description> - Client <X>
Issue ID: <JIRA-xxxx>
Category: live issue
Priority: L1
PR Link: https://...
Artifacts: curemd-app-20250615-abc123.zip
Target Env: Release server -> Production (ClientX-Server)
Planned Deploy Window: 2025-11-13, 1:00 PM PKT
Approvers: PR Approver(s), Scrum QA, Release Manager
Verification Checklist:
  1) Repro steps -> Expected result
  2) Negative case -> Expected result
  3) DB validation -> rows/values
Rollback Plan:
  - Redeploy curemd-app-20250614-old.zip
  - Run DB revert: revert-migration-20250615.sql
Owner(s): Dev: @devname | QA: @qaname | Deploy: @devops
Status: Created
Notes / Release Notes: Setup: run `setup-clientx.sql` after deploy
5) Post-deploy actions & continuous improvement
Confirmation: Scrum QA posts a confirmation message in DC Quality Assurance after successful production verification.

RCA & Lessons Learned: For L3 or repeated L1s, schedule a postmortem meeting, identify root cause, and add tests to prevent regressions.

Update Release Notes: Ensure release notes contain necessary client steps and any DB/script instructions.

Automate checks: Where possible, add automated smoke tests for high-risk flows to the release/regression suite.

6) Quick-check cheat-sheet (for day-of-deploy)
Before 12:45 PM

PR merged & approved? ✅

Deployment Task created & approved? ✅

Verification checklist in DT complete and assigned? ✅

1:00 PM

Deploy to release server → DT status Deployed ✅

1:00–2:00 PM

QA verifies release server → QA comments/approves DT by 2:00 PM ✅

2:00–3:00 PM

DevOps deploys to production → Scrum QA verifies in client environment & posts confirmation ✅

