F. Deployment Task (DT) — fields, rules, statuses
Q: What must every Deployment Task include?
A: Title, Issue ID, Category (live issue/security/etc.), Priority, PR links, Artifact/Package, Target Envs, Planned deploy window, Approvals, Verification checklist, Rollback plan, Owners, Release notes/setup instructions, Status. (The DT must have PR linked and approvals.) 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Q: What categories must be added to a Deployment Task?
A: Categories like live issue, security fix, bugfix, hotfix — category is mandatory for prioritization.

Q: Explain the typical DT status flow.
A: Created → Approved → Deployed (to release server) → SAT Done (QA-Integration acceptance) → Released (production verified) → Closed. If rollback, Rolled Back. (You can also include In Review between Created and Approved.) 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Q: What’s mandatory before deployment?
A: PR and DT approvals must be completed before the deployment window / 12:45 PM cutoff for daily releases.

Q: Who updates DT status from Approved to Deployed?
A: Developer (after deploying to the release server) or DevOps depending on who performs the release server deploy.

Q: Who updates DT to SAT Done?
A: QA-Integration after verifying the package on the release server.

G. Roles & responsibilities
Q: Who is responsible for baseline stabilization?
A: QA-Integration stabilizes baseline; developers are responsible for merging branches and resolving conflicts.

Q: Who prepares release notes?
A: QA-Integration (with technical input from developers).

Q: Who is responsible for production deployment (DevOps window)?
A: DevOps/SCM team performs production deployments (2:00–3:00 PM for daily).

Q: Who is responsible for final client verification?
A: Scrum QA verifies the fix on the specific client environment and posts confirmation.

Q: Who handles production alarms/bugs?
A: QA-Integration is responsible for alarms/bugs in production and enforces cutoffs.

H. Interfaces & special cases
Q: Why do Interfaces deployments often not align with the standard cycle?
A: Because interfaces have high impact and technical difficulty; CICD may not exist so deployments are manual and owned by the Interfaces team. They decide timelines and may deploy outside standard cycles. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Q: If an Interfaces change needs to go with the standard package, how is it handled?
A: If timelines align, Interfaces team tags required deployments to be shipped with the standard package.

I. L1 (Daily) — focused questions
Q: Define an L1 issue in this process.
A: A live, high-priority production issue reported by a client that must be fixed and deployed by the next day (Day N+1).

Q: What are the key artifacts to produce for an L1 fix?
A: PR(s), Deployment Task with all fields (PR link, verification checklist, rollback plan), test results, and logs reproducing the issue.

Q: What’s the developer’s responsibility for L1?
A: Fix code, create PR, ensure tests, update DT, deploy to release server at 1:00 PM Day N+1, and coordinate verification/rollback plan.

Q: What’s the QA’s responsibility for L1?
A: Test the fix on team servers, verify the package on release server between 1:00–2:00 PM, comment on DT by 2:00 PM, and verify in production post-deploy.

Q: Name 3 reasons an L1 fix might miss that day’s deployment.
A: PR/DT approvals after 12:45 PM; QA didn’t confirm on release server by 2:00 PM; failed verification or critical regressions discovered during verification.

Q: What is the cut-off to include an L1 fix into a daily package?
A: Approvals must be done by 12:45 PM PKT.

Q: What happens after DevOps deploys the daily package to production?
A: Scrum QA verifies the fix on the client environment and posts confirmation in the DC Quality Assurance Teams group.

J. L3 — focused questions
Q: How does an L3 differ from an L1?
A: L3 are more complex, require deeper investigation/RCAs, often involve DB schema, integrations, or cross-team changes; they may not be eligible for daily release and may require additional signoffs and testing. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Q: Who should be involved when an L3 affects interfaces or DB schema?
A: Interfaces team, DB owners, QA-Integration, DevOps, and possibly Architecture/Team Lead.

Q: Can L3 fixes go through the daily release?
A: Typically no — they often need more testing; exceptions require risk assessment and higher-level signoff.

Q: What extra deliverables should a DT for L3 contain?
A: Detailed RCA, multiple environment reproductions, DB migration scripts with rollback scripts, integration test plan, and higher-level signoffs.

Q: What is the escalation path for L3?
A: Escalate to QA-Integration/Team Lead and involve cross-functional owners; schedule for next weekly/monthly release or create an exception with approval.

K. Testing & Verification
Q: What test scenarios must the tester cover for live fixes?
A: Happy path, negative/edge cases, data integrity checks, multi-tenant checks, cross-module impact, security/permissions, basic performance/smoke, and rollback verification.

Q: Where must verification tests be documented?
A: In the Deployment Task (verification checklist). QA must comment and mark pass/fail during release/regression and after prod deploy.

Q: Who does integration/regression testing for weekly/monthly packages?
A: QA-Integration (integration/regression testing primarily done by them).

L. Rollback & Risk Management
Q: What must a rollback plan include?
A: Steps to redeploy previous artifact, DB revert scripts (if applicable), order of operations, contacts/owners, and validation steps after rollback.

Q: When should you execute the rollback plan?
A: If critical failures or regressions occur that cannot be fixed quickly during release/regression or production deploy — escalate and execute rollback to restore service.

Q: Who authors the rollback plan?
A: The developer/owner of the DT (with DevOps and QA input).

M. Scenario-based / Behavioral (practice answers)
Q: Scenario — your DT is Approved at 12:50 PM because a reviewer was late. What do you do?
A: Explain the cutoff (12:45 PM). If approvals happened after cutoff, the fix is not eligible for that day’s release. Communicate clearly to stakeholders, document why it missed the cutoff, and plan the DT for the next available package. If the issue is critical, escalate for an exception with Release Manager and document risk/rollback.

Q: Scenario — After deploying to the release server, QA finds a regression at 1:10 PM.
A: Stop promotion to production, update DT with failure details and logs, roll back release server if needed, call developer to fix or revert, follow rollback plan if regression is severe, then retest. Communicate status to stakeholders and consider delaying production deploy.

Q: Scenario — An L3 requires interface DLL replacement but CICD doesn’t exist.
A: Coordinate with Interfaces team (who owns manual deployment), ensure manual steps are documented, get approvals, perform validation in a staging environment, and schedule the manual rollout as per shipment plan or make an exception with risk approvals.

Q: Behavioral — How do you ensure maximum test coverage for a live fix?
A: Ask the developer for code locations and edge cases, collaborate with the tester to build explicit test cases (happy/edge/security/tenant), include DB checks and cross-module tests, document them in DT, and ensure QA runs them on release server and production verification.

Q: How would you handle a production alarm that comes outside working hours?
A: Follow incident response — triage severity, notify on-call owners, gather logs/replication steps, attempt quick mitigation (e.g., config toggle, revert), document steps, and prepare an L1/L3 DT for next business day or emergency patch depending on SLA.

Q: How to prevent repeated L1s?
A: Perform RCA, add regression/unit/integration tests to CI, add smoke tests for high-risk flows, improve monitoring/alerts, and update documentation and runbooks.

