diff between baseline,release and regression
ChatGPT said:
Great question — these three terms are easy to confuse because they all relate to testing/packaging, but they have distinct purposes, environments, owners and timing in CureMD’s process. Below is a short definition for each, a compact comparison table, a sample workflow showing where each fits, and a couple of mentor tips so you can answer confidently in an interview. All timings and ownership come from the CureMD Release Management doc. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Short definitions
Baseline

What: A dedicated QA-Integration environment that collects developers’ merged branches and becomes the first integrated build for QA-Integration to audit.

Purpose: Stabilize the integrated work from multiple scrum teams and find/fix integration issues early.

Owner: QA-Integration (developers merge their local branches into baseline).

When/How long: Package prep for baseline = 1 business day; Baseline testing = 4–5 business days.

Output: A stabilized “baseline package” and list of defects to fix before preparing release package. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Release

What: The release package (artifact) that is prepared for the release server and ultimately for production rollouts.

Purpose: Final packaging and validation of the software that will be promoted to production. It is the staging step immediately before live rollouts.

Owner: QA-Integration together with SCM/DevOps (they prepare and deploy the release package to the release server).

When/How long: Package prep for release = 1 business day; Release / Regression testing on release server = ~2 business days.

Output: A signed-off release package and release notes ready for live server rollouts (which start the next day). 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Regression (testing)

What: The activity of re-running functional/integration tests across the system to ensure existing functionality still works after changes. Usually performed on the release server.

Purpose: Detect regressions (broken previously-working behavior) caused by new changes and validate overall system stability prior to production.

Owner: QA-Integration performs regression testing for monthly/weekly releases; for daily fixes QA verifies the package on the release server (1:00–2:00 PM).

When/How long: For monthly release: ~2 business days on the release server; for daily fixes a targeted verification window 1:00–2:00 PM (QA must comment by 2:00 PM). 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Side-by-side comparison (quick table)
Aspect	Baseline	Release	Regression (testing)
Primary goal	Integrate & stabilize developers’ merged branches	Prepare final deployable package for production	Ensure no existing functionality is broken by the package
Environment	Baseline server (QA-Integration)	Release server → then production	Run on release server (and production for post-deploy verification)
Owner	QA-Integration (devs merge branches)	QA-Integration + SCM/DevOps	QA-Integration (monthly/weekly); Scrum QA (daily verification)
Activities	Merge branches, resolve conflicts, baseline package & audits	Build release package, create release notes, deploy to release server	Full or targeted regression test suites, smoke tests, verification checklists
Typical duration	Package prep 1 day; baseline testing 4–5 days	Package prep 1 day; release/regression testing ~2 days	Monthly: ~2 days; Daily: targeted 1:00–2:00 PM verification window
Output	Stabilized baseline build & issues list	Signed-off release package + release notes	Test results and approval/feedback to allow promotion to production
(Values/timings from CureMD Release Management.) 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Where they sit in the monthly flow (one-line flow)
Tagging → Baseline merging → Package prep for baseline → Baseline testing (4–5 days) → Release notes → Package prep for release (1 day) → Release/Regression testing on release server (~2 days) → Live server rollouts (next day).
This shows baseline → release → regression as successive gates. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Interview-friendly summary (how to answer quickly)
Baseline = early integration & stabilization (QA-Integration’s space; 4–5 days testing).

Release = final packaged build for promotion (release server; package prep + release notes).

Regression = testing that ensures nothing broke (performed on release server before production; ~2 days for monthly, short targeted window for daily fixes).
Mention owners and the timings (baseline 4–5 days, release/regression ~2 days, package prep 1 day) — interviewers like these specifics. 
20250514_ReleaseManagement (1)


Mentor tip
If asked to give an example of a problem caught at each stage:

Baseline: merge conflict or inter-feature compatibility bug.

Release: an environmental/setup script missing from release notes.

Regression: a previously-working screen breaks because a shared API changed.

That shows you understand the WHY behind each stage, not just the names.

